and, England","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Lockwood, Yorkshire, England":"Lockwood, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1417–1448":"1417–1448","1404–1434":"1404–1434","1415–1465":"1415–1465","1440–1490":"1440–1490","1442–Male":"1442–Deceased","1444–Female":"1444–Deceased","1446–Male":"1446–Deceased","1448–Male":"1448–Deceased","1378–Male":"1378–Deceased","1375–1486":"1375–1486","1440":"1440","1490":"1490","1448":"1448","1415":"1415","1404":"1404","1446":"1446","1434":"1434","1444":"1444","1378":"1378","about 1438":"about 1438","1465":"1465","1442":"1442","ABT 1398":"about 1398","1486":"1486","1375":"1375","1417":"1417","Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England":"Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Lockwood, Yorkshire, England":"Lockwood, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lockwood","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from one of three places called Lockwood, one in Yorkshire, one in North Yorkshire and another in Staffordshire. The Yorkshire and Staffordshire placenames both derive from Old English <i>loc</i> ‘lock, enclosure, fold’ + <i>wudu</i> ‘wood’. The North Yorkshire placename derives from Old English <i>loc</i> + Old Norse <i>vithr</i> ‘wood’. The surname appears to have migrated to East Anglia."],"variants":[{"name":"Logwood","meanings":["Perhaps an altered form of   Lockwood  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Agnes Lockwood was born in 1417, in Lockwood, Yorkshire, England, her father, Henry de Lockwood, was 40 and her mother, Lady Agnes De La Schaw, was 42. She married Sir John Anderson about 1438. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1448, in Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England, at the age of 31."},"et":{"1417–1448":"1417–1448","1404–1434":"1404–1434","1415–1465":"1415–1465","1440–1490":"1440–1490","1442–Male":"1442–Surnud","1444–Female":"1444–Surnud","1446–Male":"1446–Surnud","1448–Male":"1448–Surnud","1378–Male":"1378–Surnud","1375–1486":"1375–1486","1440":"1440","1490":"1490","1448":"1448","1415":"1415","1404":"1404","1446":"1446","1434":"1434","1444":"1444","1378":"1378","about 1438":"umbes 1438","1465":"1465","1442":"1442","ABT 1398":"umbes 1398","1486":"1486","1375":"1375","1417":"1417","Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England":"Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Lockwood, Yorkshire, England":"Lockwood, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1417–1448":"1417–1448","1404–1434":"1404–1434","1415–1465":"1415–1465","1440–1490":"1440–1490","1442–Male":"1442–Kuollut","1444–Female":"1444–Kuollut","1446–Male":"1446–Kuollut","1448–Male":"1448–Kuollut","1378–Male":"1378–Kuollut","1375–1486":"1375–1486","1440":"1440","1490":"1490","1448":"1448","1415":"1415","1404":"1404","1446":"1446